Still this is all solving the symptom, and not the underlying problem, which is the flat reward curve. As long as you have a flat reward curve, there is apparently no significant competition between miners (i.e. miner UIDs) and one party can pump their revenue by registering multiple miners, up to the point where the reg fee equals the reward.

If you can somehow ensure that one miner can't win twice (which in SN9 and SN29 is easy, and here, idk) the whole UID pressure problem is instantly solved.

But for now, to avoid chain spam and create a level playing field, if you don't observe these things you might as well stop trying to register in case of UID pressure:
- there can only be one reg per block, and typically 3 reg per tempo (but see below)
- a tempo is typically 100, but check `tempo = subtensor.query_module(module='SubtensorModule', name='AdjustmentInterval', params=[netuid]).value`
- also check `subtensor.query_module(module='SubtensorModule', name='NetworkRegistrationAllowed', params=[netuid]).value` before attempting register
- and check `trpi = subtensor.query_module(module='SubtensorModule', name='TargetRegistrationsPerInterval', params=[netuid]).value`
- and check `rti = subtensor.query_module(module='SubtensorModule', name='RegistrationsThisInterval', params=[netuid]).value`
- there is a magic factor of 3 hardcoded in subtensor, where if `rti >= trpi` you cannot register anymore, and you have to wait
- make sure to check `burn = subtensor.query_module(module='SubtensorModule', name='Burn', params=[netuid]).value` and compare its value to some upper limit; note that in the new tempo, the burn will have changed (prediction of new value is possible, left as an exercise to the reader, ranges from halving to doubling)
- this is VERY IMPORTANT: `last_adjustment_block = subtensor.query_module(module='SubtensorModule', name='LastAdjustmentBlock', params=[netuid]).value` ...
- ... because `next_tempo = last_adjustment_block + tempo` and before that, you'll just be spamming, with no chance of success, and actually only increasing the chance that the final register call will fail!
- so then, simply spin:
```while subtensor.block < next_tempo:
   time.sleep(1)
```
and after this loop immediately push the reg extrinsic.
- ofc use a local subtensor!
When doing this in parallel, **use different coldkeys,** as every coldkey has its own nonce and your parallel processes will be working against each other.

Validating the SWE-Bench tasks has been *EXTREMELY* expensive. Currently, validators have been paying $50-200/day in API fees. At Team Rizzo, we understand how expensive validation can be and we are always working towards being part of the solution rather than the problem.

The provisioning key will be used to generate temporary keys for the validator to use in order to evaluate your submission. I implore any miners to bring up any issues or security concerns they may have with this solution.
